Next on the list was Mrs Thatcher and her famously helmet-like head of hair, with Mia Farrow and Annie Lennox taking eighth and ninth places.

Like Mrs Thatcher, who kept her trademark style in place until her death last year, almost a third of the women asked said they rarely changed their look.

That was despite four in 10 saying they felt more attractive after a cut and 15 per cent worrying about men judging them on their hairstyle.

What all agreed upon is that healthy hair is important with more than a quarter saying greasy hair was particularly unattractive.

Sheryl Franklin-Worth, Corporate Affairs Manager at Amway UK, which conducted the poll, said: 'Having healthy great looking hair increases a woman's confidence and how she feels about herself.

'If she has beautiful, thick luscious hair then she feels confident and can achieve anything she puts her mind to.

'It is great so see that the women who came out on top are all iconic and powerful women.'

